    "claim_lines": [
      "**Agentic RAG** is a retrieval-augmented generation pattern where an LLM acts more like an autonomous agent: it can **plan**, **decide when and what to retrieve**, **rewrite queries**, **use tools**, and **iterate over multiple retrieval/reasoning steps** before answering. In contrast, **standard RAG** is usually a mostly fixed pipeline: **retrieve relevant context once, append it to the prompt, then generate the answer**. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/concepts/retrieval-augmented-generation?utm_source=openai))",
      "Practically, agentic RAG is useful for **complex, multi-hop, or ambiguous questions** because the system can refine its search as it learns more. The tradeoff is **more latency, higher cost, and more orchestration complexity**, plus more opportunities for compounding mistakes across steps. Standard RAG is simpler, cheaper, and easier to control, but it can struggle when one retrieval pass is not enough. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.09136?utm_source=openai))"
    ],
